---
import DocsLayout from '../../layouts/DocsLayout.astro';
import CodeExample from '../../components/CodeExample.astro';

const utilityExamples = `.visually-hidden
.flow
.text-center
.cluster
.switcher`;

const usefulUtilities = `.visually-hidden {
    position: absolute;
    inline-size: 1px;
    block-size: 1px;
    overflow: hidden;
    clip-path: inset(50%);
    white-space: nowrap;
}

.flow > * + * {
    margin-block-start: var(--flow-space, 1em);
}`;

const avoidExample = `<article class="p-4 mb-4 bg-white rounded shadow text-center grid gap-4">
    <h2 class="text-xl font-bold mb-2">Product title</h2>
    <p class="text-sm text-muted mb-4">Product description</p>
</article>`;

const betterExample = `<article class="product-card">
    <h2 class="title">Product title</h2>
    <p class="description">Product description</p>
</article>`;
---

<DocsLayout
    title="LSCSS Utilities"
    description="Utility classes in Layered Semantic CSS, including when to use utilities, when to use components, and how to avoid class soup."
    schemaType="TechArticle"
>
    <section class="site-hero">
        <p class="eyebrow">Utilities</p>

        <h1>
            Utility classes
        </h1>

        <p class="intro">
            Utilities should remain small, explicit, reusable, and boring. They
            support component architecture. They do not replace it.
        </p>
    </section>

    <nav class="section-nav" aria-label="Utilities sections">
        <a href="#good-utilities">Good utilities</a>
        <a href="#examples">Examples</a>
        <a href="#components-vs-utilities">Components vs utilities</a>
        <a href="#avoid">Avoid</a>
    </nav>

    <section id="good-utilities" class="content-block">
        <h2>
            What makes a good utility
        </h2>

        <p>
            A useful utility does one small job. It should be predictable across
            the project and should not need local overrides to behave properly.
        </p>

        <ul>
            <li>Use utilities for repeated low-level patterns.</li>
            <li>Keep utilities independent of specific components.</li>
            <li>Prefer semantic components for meaningful UI structures.</li>
            <li>Avoid utilities that hide complex design decisions.</li>
            <li>Do not use utilities as a dumping ground for missing architecture.</li>
        </ul>
    </section>

    <section id="examples" class="content-block">
        <h2>
            Common utility names
        </h2>

        <CodeExample code={utilityExamples} />

        <p>
            These names describe small repeatable behaviours, not whole
            components.
        </p>

        <CodeExample code={usefulUtilities} />
    </section>

    <section id="components-vs-utilities" class="content-block">
        <h2>
            Components vs utilities
        </h2>

        <p>
            Use a component when the structure has meaning. Use a utility when
            the behaviour is small, generic, and reusable in many places.
        </p>

        <p>
            If a group of utilities keeps appearing together, it is probably a
            component trying to escape.
        </p>
    </section>

    <section id="avoid" class="content-block">
        <h2>
            Avoid class soup
        </h2>

        <p>
            A long chain of utilities can make markup harder to scan, harder to
            refactor, and harder to explain to the next developer.
        </p>

        <CodeExample code={avoidExample} language="html" />

        <p>
            Prefer a semantic component when the HTML represents a real UI
            pattern.
        </p>

        <CodeExample code={betterExample} language="html" />
    </section>
</DocsLayout>
